<A name=Alpha_Beta></A><A name=AlphaBeta></A><span class=moyet>==</span><span class=blogtitle><b>Alpha Beta</b></span><span class=moyet>==</span>

<p>

Alpha Beta is not only a name of a
<a href="http://www.groceteria.com/store/regional-chains/a-e/alpha-beta/">defunct
</a>grocery chain|,
it is also a view of human reproductive strategy: Alpha males end up
having more access to females and, therefore, more offspring, while Beta
males end up having fewer offspring.

<p>

The paper
<i>Strong gender differences in reproductive success variance,</i>
<i>and the times to the most recent common ancestors</i>
by Maroussia Favre and Didier Sornette presents evidence that, historically,
men had about a 40% chance of propagating their genetic code, while women
have had an 80% of doing so.

<p>

One can read this paper here: <A href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1203.6231.pdf">http:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/arxiv<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>.org<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/pdf<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/1203<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>.6231<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>.pdf</A>
(PDF file)

